{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox company | name = Jewish Telegraphic Agency | logo = Jewish-Telegraphic-Agency.jpg | caption = | type = [[Non-profit organization|Not-for-profit news agency]] | traded_as = | genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies --> | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = {{Start date and age|1917|02|06}} | founder = Jacob Landau | defunct = | location_city = New York City | location_country = USA | location = | locations = | area_served = | key_people = Andrew Silow-Carroll, Editor-in-Chief | industry = [[News media]] | products = [[News agency|Wire service]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Joe Sterling|title=Jewish paper's column catches Secret Service's eye|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/21/us/jewish-president-threat/index.html|accessdate=14 October 2013|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=January 22, 2012}}</ref> | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies --> | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = {{official URL}} | footnotes = | intl = }} The '''Jewish Telegraphic Agency''' ('''JTA''') is an international [[news agency]] and [[wire service]] serving Jewish community [[newspaper]]s and media around the world, with about 70 syndication clients listed on its web site.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.jta.org/about-us|website=Jewish Telegraph Agency|publisher=Jewish Telegraph Agency|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>
==History== The JTA was founded on February 6, 1917, by Jacob Landau as the Jewish Correspondence Bureau in [[The Hague]] with the mandate of collecting and disseminating news affecting the Jewish communities around the world,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A808AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA182 |title=American Jewish year book |publisher= |year=1920 |author=American Jewish Committee, Jewish Publication Society of America |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iCiwUyWDBu4C&pg=PA91 |title=Religion and our divided denominations |publisher= |year=1971 |author=Willard Learoyd Sperry |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name="google1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5DuagGR8RNsC&pg=PA143 |title=Guide to the YIVO Archives |publisher= |year=1998 |author= YIVO Archives, Fruma Mohrer, Marek Web, Yivo Institute for Jewish Research|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E8qqhylTDZYC&pg=PA490 |title=Deutsches Judentum unter dem Nationalsozialismus |publisher=Mohr Siebeck |date= |author=Otto Dov Kulka |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref> especially from the European war fronts.<ref name="Sarna">{{cite book |url=http://www.brandeis.edu/hornstein/pdfs/publications/American%20Jewish%20Press%20-%20Oxford%20Handbook.pdf |title=The Oxford Handbook of Religion and the American News Media |author=Jonathan D. Sarna |chapter=The American Jewish Press |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=544}}</ref> In 1919, it moved to London, under its current name.<ref name="google1"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AceeVqhPHtcC&pg=PA476 |title=Isaiah Berlin; Letters, 1928–1946 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2004 |author1=Isaiah Berlin |author2=Henry Hardy |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://leobaeck.oxfordjournals.org/content/54/1/219.short |title=Diplomacy in the Diaspora: The Jewish Telegraphic Agency in Berlin (1922–1933) |work=Leo Baeck Institute Yearbook|date=July 28, 2009 |author=Verena Dohrn |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>
In 1922, the JTA moved its headquarters to New York City.<ref name="google1"/> By 1925, over 400 newspapers (Jewish and general) subscribed to the JTA. Its cable service improved the quality and range of Jewish periodicals.<ref name="Sarna"/> Today, it has correspondents in [[Washington, DC]], [[Jerusalem]], Moscow and 30 other cities in North and South America, Israel, Europe, Africa and Australia. The JTA is committed to covering news of interest to the Jewish community with [[journalistic objectivity|journalistic detachment]].<ref name="Sarna"/>
In 1940, the JTA spawned the Overseas News Agency (ONA).<ref>{{cit news | newspaper = JTA | date = July 14, 1940 | title = Overseas News Agency Launched | url = https://www.jta.org/1940/07/14/archive/overseas-news-agency-launched}}</ref> Although designed to appear like a normal news agency, it was in fact secretly funded by the British intelligence service [[MI6]].<ref name=Grisar>{{cite news | author = PJ Grisar | title = Sharks Defending Britain From Nazis? How ‘Fake News’ Helped Foil Hitler | url = https://forward.com/culture/412422/sharks-defending-britain-from-nazis-how-fake-news-helped-foil-hitler/ | newspaper = [[The Forward]] | date = October 22, 2018}}</ref> ONA provided press credentials to British spies and planted fake news stories in US newspapers.<ref name=Grisar/>
The JTA is a not-for-profit corporation governed by an independent board of directors. It claims no allegiance to any specific branch of [[Judaism]] or political viewpoint. "We respect the many Jewish and Israel advocacy organizations out there, but JTA has a different mission — to provide readers and clients with balanced and dependable reporting," wrote JTA editor-in-chief and CEO and publisher Ami Eden. He gave the example of the JTA's coverage of the [[MV Mavi Marmara|''Mavi Marmara'' activist ship]].<ref name="Forward">[http://forward.com/articles/179453/fledgling-jewish-news-service-rocks-boat-with-stri/ Fledgling Jewish News Service Rocks Boat With Strident Pro-Israel Message, Challenges JTA for Slice of Jewish Newspaper Market, By Josh Nathan-Kazis, Forward, issue of July 5, 2013]</ref>
