{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}} [[File:Lutherstadt Wittenberg 09-2016 photo06.jpg|thumb|"Thesentür" (door of the theses) memorial at Schlosskirche in [[Lutherstadt Wittenberg]]]]
'''''The Wittenburg Door''''', sometimes known as simply '''''The Door''''', was a [[Christianity|Christian]] [[satire]] and [[humor]] magazine, published bimonthly by the [[non-profit]] [[Trinity Foundation (Dallas)|Trinity Foundation]] based in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]], [[Texas]].<ref>''Encyclopedia of evangelicalism'', Randall Herbert Balmer, Verlag Westminster John Knox Press, 2002 {{ISBN|0-664-22409-1}}</ref> The magazine started publication in 1971<ref>{{cite web|title=About The Wittenburg Door|url=http://www.wittenburgdoor.com/about-us.html|publisher=The Wittenburg Door|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> and ceased publication in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 'Lost' Wittenburg Door Interview With Baptist Heretic/Legend E. Glenn Hinson | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/bert-montgomery/e-glenn-hinson-wittenburg-door-interview_b_1775687.html |date=October 12, 2012 |author=Montgomery, Bert |publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> The title was a reference to [[the Ninety-Five Theses]] written by [[Martin Luther]] in 1517 that he is believed to have posted on the door of the [[All Saints' Church, Wittenberg|All Saints' Church in Wittenberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alard-von-rohr.com/switzerland/Reformation_Tour.pdf|title=Alard von Rohr-Demmin|publisher=}}</ref>
